00:01:58.570 --> 00:02:00.986
I don't know if I am mindful
all the time, as Rachel said,

00:02:00.986 --> 00:02:04.980
but I do teach it a lot.

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:09.940
And sort of in that
evolution, my own evolution,

00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:14.440
where I started out using
methods of meditation

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:17.980
to try to be more aware and
to understand myself more,

00:02:17.980 --> 00:02:21.450
and really frankly, to be
a lot happier than I was.

00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:24.170
I was 18 years old
when I went to India.

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:25.670
And I was a junior in college.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:30.030
And I went through a
university program.

00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:34.697
And that, of course, was why I
went, because I looked around

00:02:34.697 --> 00:02:36.280
where I was going
to school and I just

00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:39.620
didn't see the actual
how-to, the ways to meditate,

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:41.440
to bring it to life anywhere.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:44.710
And it took that kind of
journey in those days.

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:46.510
So I've been really
interested just sort

00:02:46.510 --> 00:02:49.760
of watching this wave
happen and realized,

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:52.630
you don't have to go anywhere
anymore if you don't want to.

00:02:52.630 --> 00:02:54.760
And look at that.

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:56.840
What does that mean
for us here and now?

00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:59.930
So I started with
mindfulness practice,

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:02.530
which was enormous for me.

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:06.100
And I also heard that there
were different techniques

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:10.570
available that would emphasize
qualities like loving-kindness

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:11.330
and compassion.

00:03:11.330 --> 00:03:14.980
So loving-kindness is a
really odd term, I know.

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:19.300
And it it's not, generally
speaking, the kind of term

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:22.790
you hear people talking
about casually somewhere.

00:03:22.790 --> 00:03:25.660
And that makes me
concerned that that

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:28.450
might make the quality
itself seem somewhat arcane

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:30.839
and removed from
day-to-day life.

00:03:30.839 --> 00:03:31.630
Like, what is that?

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:34.480
Like something
quaint, something sort

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:36.880
of sanctimonious or
something like that.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:39.520
But actually, it's meant
to be a live, vital sense

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:44.050
of connection, to
not feel so isolated,

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:48.010
not to isolate others,
to have a sense of being

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:49.630
a part of a greater whole.

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:51.760
As one friend of
mine quipped as we

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:55.220
were driving along somewhere,
caught in terrible traffic,

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:59.050
and they were complaining
bitterly about the traffic,

00:03:59.050 --> 00:04:01.940
and the traffic was so
wretched and so terrible.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:05.995
And then they paused and said,
I guess we're the traffic, too.

00:04:05.995 --> 00:04:08.170
You know, what's it
like when we're not

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:11.860
considering ourselves separate
and apart in those ways?

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:15.970
Where the kind of constructs of
self and other and us and them,

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:19.959
where the great big other out
there are seen as constructs.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:21.550
They may be useful.

00:04:21.550 --> 00:04:24.170
They may be inappropriate
in certain situations.

00:04:24.170 --> 00:04:25.870
But they're just constructs.

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:28.870
The reality is that we live
in an interconnected universe.

00:04:28.870 --> 00:04:30.790
And here we are, right?

00:04:30.790 --> 00:04:34.210
It's a world that's pointing
to that all of the time.

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:37.510
But our values, our
behavior, don't always

00:04:37.510 --> 00:04:39.880
reflect that truth.

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:43.420
And so being able
to see more clearly,

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:45.850
to see more accurately,
to see the interconnected

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:50.500
nature of things is one
of the strongest ways

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:54.850
to leap into a sense
of loving-kindness,

00:04:54.850 --> 00:04:57.580
just honoring that
state of connection.

00:04:57.580 --> 00:04:59.440
Loving-kindness, or
love in this case,

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:01.350
since I'm now using
the word love,

00:05:01.350 --> 00:05:03.460
doesn't mean you like everybody.

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:06.580
It actually doesn't even mean
you necessarily like anybody.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:10.680
But we do understand
our lives have something

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:12.160
to do with one another.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:14.460
It's a deep, deep
acknowledgement

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:17.940
that we do live in this kind
of world of connection--

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:20.580
in effect, that we
are all the traffic.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:22.030
I have a friend,
Bob Thurman, who

00:05:22.030 --> 00:05:24.570
is a professor of Buddhist
studies at Columbia University.

00:05:24.570 --> 00:05:28.900
And he uses this image a lot--
which I actually, I think,

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:30.860
I use much more than he does--

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:35.910
where he says, imagine you're
on a subway and these martians

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:38.364
come, and they zap
the subway cars

00:05:38.364 --> 00:05:39.780
so that those of
you who are there

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:42.740
are going to be
together forever.

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:43.870
He says, what do you do?

00:05:43.870 --> 00:05:46.191
Like, if somebody is
hungry, you feed them.

00:05:46.191 --> 00:05:48.440
If somebody's freaking out,
you try to calm them down,

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.650
not because you necessarily like
them or you approve of them,

00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:54.320
but because you're going
to be together forever.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:56.150
So guess what?

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:58.140
There's a lot of truth to that.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:02.660
So this notion of
interconnection

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:05.120
isn't always like--
it's not sentimental.

00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:09.110
It's not saccharin, sweet.

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.600
It's not even very
nice sometimes.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:14.630
But it is that
fundamental recognition

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:18.140
that what happens over there
doesn't nicely stay over there.

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:21.030
It really ripples out over here.

00:06:21.030 --> 00:06:23.660
And what we do, where we put
our energy, what we care about,

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:26.080
it matters because it's
going to ripple out

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:27.350
in just that same way.

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:30.700
And here we are in a world
where science is showing us this

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:33.020
and economics is
showing us this.

00:06:33.020 --> 00:06:34.910
And certainly,
environmental consciousness

00:06:34.910 --> 00:06:36.210
is showing us this.

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:38.420
Even epidemiology
is showing us this.

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:40.940
Here we are.

00:06:40.940 --> 00:06:43.780
And can our lives actually
reflect that truth

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:46.194
in deeper and deeper ways?

00:06:46.194 --> 00:06:48.110
So sometimes when I tell
that story about Bob,

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:49.560
I go on to tell this story.

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:55.250
I was in New York City once,
sitting on an airplane, which--

00:06:55.250 --> 00:06:57.410
trying to get to Tucson.

00:06:57.410 --> 00:07:03.210
And the plane sat on the tarmac
for about 4 and 1/2 hours,

00:07:03.210 --> 00:07:04.840
in what, looking
back, I sometimes

00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:07.610
now call the breakdown
of civilization,

00:07:07.610 --> 00:07:09.449
because it was getting
hotter and hotter

00:07:09.449 --> 00:07:11.240
and people were getting
angrier and angrier

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:15.190
and screaming and yelling,
like, get me off this plane.

00:07:15.190 --> 00:07:17.360
And I wasn't feeling
all that chiper myself.

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:18.290
You know, I was
sitting there thinking,

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:19.730
I'm paying rent
in New York City.

00:07:19.730 --> 00:07:21.360
If they'd only let
me off the plane,

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:23.690
I could go home and
try again tomorrow.

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:26.600
At one point, the pilot sort of
took command of the aircraft.

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:28.730
He got on the PA
system and he said,

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:31.390
no one is getting
off this plane.

00:07:31.390 --> 00:07:34.640
So I was sitting there
and not feeling very good.

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:36.610
And then all of a sudden,
that image of Bob's

00:07:36.610 --> 00:07:40.480
that I had used so often in
teaching came up in my mind.

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:44.410
Like, imagine you're on a
subway and these martians

00:07:44.410 --> 00:07:47.274
come, and they
zapped the subway car

00:07:47.274 --> 00:07:48.690
so that those of
you who are there

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:51.276
are going to be
together forever.

00:07:51.276 --> 00:07:52.650
And I looked around
the airplane,

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:55.410
and I thought, maybe
these are my people.

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:59.050
Here we are, maybe forever.

00:07:59.050 --> 00:08:01.427
And I realized in that
moment a good deal of my ire

00:08:01.427 --> 00:08:03.760
was this feeling of, like,
how long am I stuck with you?

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:04.885
And it's like, oh, forever.

00:08:04.885 --> 00:08:05.790
Deal.

00:08:05.790 --> 00:08:06.480
Right?

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:07.650
This is it.

00:08:07.650 --> 00:08:10.560
How are we going to
deal with one another?

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:13.320
And that very much
is the sensibility

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:18.960
I bring into the practice of
loving-kindness meditation.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.025
We can develop
deepened qualities

00:08:21.025 --> 00:08:22.960
like compassion
and self-compassion

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:26.250
and understand them,
which is very important,

00:08:26.250 --> 00:08:30.820
and really explore
those qualities

00:08:30.820 --> 00:08:32.110
in lots of different ways.

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:36.250
Obviously, life lends us
a lot of opportunities

00:08:36.250 --> 00:08:38.230
just every day.

00:08:38.230 --> 00:08:40.299
Doing a simple
method of meditation

00:08:40.299 --> 00:08:44.260
like putting your attention
on the feeling of the breath,

00:08:44.260 --> 00:08:49.260
some object like that, and
having to continually return

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:51.510
your attention to
that object will

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:54.630
deepen the qualities of
loving-kindness and, first,

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:57.330
self-compassion,
which will blossom out

00:08:57.330 --> 00:08:58.830
into compassion for others.

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:02.480
Because there's actually no
way to do it successfully

00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:03.900
without that deepening.

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:05.700
Even if it's never
voiced, it's never

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:09.210
articulated, it's never named,
that's what we're actually

00:09:09.210 --> 00:09:10.400
doing.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:11.500
So I got to India.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:15.150
And I first learned
meditation in the context

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:16.500
of an intensive 10-day retreat.

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:18.990
That's how I started.

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:22.390
And the first
instruction I was given

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:25.970
was, sit down and
feel your breath.

00:09:25.970 --> 00:09:28.030
And first of all, I
was very disappointed.

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:30.070
I thought, feel my breath?

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:31.621
I came all the way to India.

00:09:31.621 --> 00:09:34.120
You know, where's the magical,
esoteric, fantastic technique

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:36.385
that's going to
transform my whole life?

00:09:36.385 --> 00:09:38.200
I thought, feel my breath?

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:40.100
I could've stayed home
to feel my breath.

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:42.070
And then I thought, eh,
how hard can this be?

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:43.600
It's going to be a snap.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:46.240
Well, haha, it wasn't that easy.

00:09:46.240 --> 00:09:47.680
I'd thought, OK,
what will it be?

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:50.890
Like 800 breaths, 900
breaths before my mind

00:09:50.890 --> 00:09:52.450
starts to wander?

00:09:52.450 --> 00:09:57.300
And to my astonishment, it was
like one breath or two breaths

00:09:57.300 --> 00:09:58.150
and I would be gone.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:00.310
And I'd be way gone.

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:03.670
And then comes the magic
moment where you think,

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:06.980
been some time since
I last felt a breath.

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:09.060
And I was told over and
over and over again,

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:11.810
but did not believe
that that was actually

00:10:11.810 --> 00:10:13.670
the critical moment
in the whole process,

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:19.810
because that's the moment of
being able to be different.

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:22.190
Instead of judging yourself
and being harsh and feeling

00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:27.740
like a failure and spending
the next four hours, say, just

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:30.320
in that rant about
yourself, thereby extending

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.750
the period of the
distraction and leaving

00:10:32.750 --> 00:10:35.480
yourself exhausted
and demoralized,

00:10:35.480 --> 00:10:37.670
we learn how to let go.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.315
Just let go gently.

00:10:39.315 --> 00:10:41.540
What one of my teachers
called exercising

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:42.960
the letting-go muscle.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:44.660
And we learned how
to begin again.

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:46.370
Just let go and come back.

00:10:46.370 --> 00:10:50.230
And that coming back is an
expression of self-compassion,

00:10:50.230 --> 00:10:54.110
because the nearly
overwhelming temptation is just

00:10:54.110 --> 00:10:58.950
to go on that rant, you know,
and to get lost in that.

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:00.810
And this is a chance
to be different,

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:02.670
which is a challenge, right?

00:11:02.670 --> 00:11:04.560
The building block
of that difference

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:06.535
is some kindness
towards yourself.

00:11:06.535 --> 00:11:09.270
And the reason I said it's
so important to understand it

00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:12.360
is because that doesn't
mean being lazy or not

00:11:12.360 --> 00:11:15.900
having standards of excellence
or not having an edge,

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:17.810
not having commitment.

00:11:17.810 --> 00:11:20.850
It's actually a
pretty radical notion

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:25.560
of what is the best way to
succeed and make a change

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:28.300
and learn something new.

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:32.230
Because think of all that
time we spend in those rants,

00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:35.030
and think of how
we feel at the end.

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:37.390
So that's why we
say that meditation

00:11:37.390 --> 00:11:40.160
is a practice of resilience.

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:43.480
So that's a tremendous way,
whatever process we do,

00:11:43.480 --> 00:11:48.910
of building that almost
unspoken but known sense

00:11:48.910 --> 00:11:52.180
of loving-kindness.

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:55.090
We practice through insight,
through understanding,

00:11:55.090 --> 00:11:59.560
through anything we do, anything
we perceive anew in a way

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:02.620
so that we see our
assumptions of aloneness

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:06.520
and a sense of isolation,
our assumptions

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:10.330
of fundamental difference
are really assumptions.

00:12:10.330 --> 00:12:12.560
And we get to question them.

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:15.980
You know, is it so
that this person

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:23.660
at the other end of the world is
so very different, ultimately?

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:24.580
Is it?

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:26.075
Well, let's check it out.

00:12:26.075 --> 00:12:29.460
We live in a time where
we can check it out.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:31.830
And we can check it
out within as well--

00:12:31.830 --> 00:12:35.170
the ways we categorize people,
the ways we dismiss people,

00:12:35.170 --> 00:12:37.730
the ways we don't see people.

00:12:37.730 --> 00:12:40.210
If you think about all the
people, perhaps in your life,

00:12:40.210 --> 00:12:44.708
that you tend to look
through instead of look at.

00:12:44.708 --> 00:12:47.290
The places where we
create an other, not

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:49.840
even just through
bias or prejudice,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:51.770
but just indifference.

00:12:51.770 --> 00:12:52.960
Like, who doesn't count?

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:55.110
Who doesn't matter?

00:12:55.110 --> 00:12:57.490
And what happens when
you look more carefully?

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:58.170
That's all.

00:12:58.170 --> 00:13:04.050
It's not trying to exist in,
awash with a certain feeling,

00:13:04.050 --> 00:13:08.280
but just looking more carefully,
seeing things more as they are.

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:12.330
There's this tremendous
opening into that kind

00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:14.670
of state of connection.

00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:17.500
And there are ways of
actually stretching.

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:19.830
It's kind of practicing
in certain ways,

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:22.790
practicing paying
attention differently,

00:13:22.790 --> 00:13:29.280
so that we are putting our
attention in a place where

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:32.940
these qualities of
connection can emerge.

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:38.014
The question comes up, you know,
what do we pay attention to?

00:13:38.014 --> 00:13:39.430
If we're thinking
about ourselves,

00:13:39.430 --> 00:13:44.700
are we singularly consumed with
just the mistakes we've made?

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:47.910
Or can we leave a little
room for a bigger picture?

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:50.130
Those mistakes may be true.

00:13:50.130 --> 00:13:51.820
If you come to the
end of the day,

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:54.240
if you're almost
evaluating yourself,

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:56.760
yes, maybe you weren't perfect.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:59.340
But what is the standard
of perfection anyway?

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:02.340
And what if we only
obsess about and are

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:06.420
consumed with and captivated
by those mistakes,

00:14:06.420 --> 00:14:10.070
to the detriment of there
being a more truthful picture?

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:13.350
Can we give a little air
time to the other side?

00:14:13.350 --> 00:14:15.230
Can we?

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:18.460
So what do we pay attention to?

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:19.930
And who do we pay attention to?

00:14:19.930 --> 00:14:25.175
As I said before, who can
we look through rather than

00:14:25.175 --> 00:14:25.675
look at?

00:14:28.580 --> 00:14:30.420
And how do we pay attention?

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:31.560
How present are we?

00:14:31.560 --> 00:14:33.700
How scattered are we?

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:35.880
How much are we looking
around the room,

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:37.880
seeing who might be more
interesting to talk to?

00:14:37.880 --> 00:14:41.310
Who have we already decided,
oh, well, I heard about you,

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:41.810
you know?

00:14:41.810 --> 00:14:42.518
You're like that.

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:47.720
No need to listen.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:51.110
And if we see those things,
if we see those habits

00:14:51.110 --> 00:14:53.840
or we see those
tendencies, we can actually

00:14:53.840 --> 00:14:56.090
relax them or
relinquish them and be

00:14:56.090 --> 00:14:58.190
there in a different
way, which is

00:14:58.190 --> 00:15:01.760
the ground for a certain
sense of connection

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:03.830
that I'm calling
loving-kindness.

00:15:03.830 --> 00:15:05.360
These days I call
it love, partly

00:15:05.360 --> 00:15:07.010
because that's the book title.

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:12.820
But actually, people like Bob
Thurman, who is a scholar,

00:15:12.820 --> 00:15:17.080
has said to me in the
past, loving-kindness

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:19.460
is so quirky a term.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:21.440
Like, what does that mean?

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:23.980
You should just say love.

00:15:23.980 --> 00:15:28.210
And so I'm experimenting,
clearly, with that.

00:15:28.210 --> 00:15:31.940
Love is a complicated,
complicated term.

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:35.280
What do we mean by love?

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:39.550
Sometimes we really frankly
mean a medium of exchange.

00:15:39.550 --> 00:15:43.310
I will love you as long
as you love me in return

00:15:43.310 --> 00:15:47.260
and as long as you evidence
that in these 15 ways.

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:49.990
I will love myself as long
as I never make a mistake.

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:54.160
Well, what does
that mean really?

00:15:54.160 --> 00:15:56.050
We know the fragility
of that state

00:15:56.050 --> 00:15:58.362
and the breakability
of that state.

00:15:58.362 --> 00:16:00.070
But really, we're
talking about something

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:03.840
that can be more
sustained or more renewed,

00:16:03.840 --> 00:16:07.770
that can really support us.

00:16:07.770 --> 00:16:13.760
When we talk about loving an
other, what does that mean?

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:16.280
In some ways, the
evolution of this book

00:16:16.280 --> 00:16:19.550
actually is almost
entirely based on one line

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:24.230
from a movie, which the movie
is called "Dan In Real Life."

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:28.700
It's maybe now 13, 14 years
old, something like that.

00:16:28.700 --> 00:16:31.490
My god-daughter was in
it, so I can kind of

00:16:31.490 --> 00:16:32.900
place the movie by her.

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:34.880
She was really a very
little girl then,

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:37.790
and she just went to college.

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:44.640
So the line in the movie
is, "Love is not a feeling;

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:46.810
it's an ability."

00:16:46.810 --> 00:16:48.890
Love is not a feeling;
it's an ability.

00:16:48.890 --> 00:16:51.850
And this is very
resonant with what

00:16:51.850 --> 00:16:56.470
we call loving-kindness or
even the state of compassion.

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:58.300
Of course, it is
a feeling as well,

00:16:58.300 --> 00:17:02.300
and it's a feeling that in
terms of cultural pressure

00:17:02.300 --> 00:17:06.619
and conditioning we yearn for,
we want, we identify with,

00:17:06.619 --> 00:17:09.569
or the lack of with.

00:17:09.569 --> 00:17:13.230
But think of it for a moment
as an ability instead.

00:17:13.230 --> 00:17:15.930
It's a response
mechanism, right?

00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:17.329
It's a way of being with.

00:17:17.329 --> 00:17:19.060
It's a worldview.

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:23.050
It's a way of being present
with ourselves and with others.

00:17:23.050 --> 00:17:25.829
It's a way of caring.

00:17:25.829 --> 00:17:30.840
Like looking around that
subway and thinking,

00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:33.800
we're going to be
together forever.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:38.980
So it's a matter of inclusion
rather than exclusion.

00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:42.640
It's seeing the assumptions
that come up in one's mind

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:45.850
and being willing
to question them.

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:52.520
Because in the end, it doesn't
make that much sense, really,

00:17:52.520 --> 00:17:54.470
that we don't all
want to be happy,

00:17:54.470 --> 00:18:00.360
that we don't want a sense of
belonging, things like that.

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:02.880
Love is an ability.

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:04.750
And I was very
captivated by that line,

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:07.240
"love is not a feeling;
it's an ability,"

00:18:07.240 --> 00:18:11.020
in part because it did so
resonate with experiences

00:18:11.020 --> 00:18:15.380
I had had doing
loving-kindness meditation.

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:19.300
So in addition to just
concentration techniques

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:23.230
like being with the breath and
kind of the stealth cultivation

00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:27.040
of self-compassion and seeing
more clearly and having

00:18:27.040 --> 00:18:30.190
more insight, there
are definitely

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:33.610
techniques that are
devoted to the deepening

00:18:33.610 --> 00:18:34.480
of those qualities.

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:37.690
And I first did them
really intensively

00:18:37.690 --> 00:18:42.100
when I was in Burma in 1985,
doing a three-month period

00:18:42.100 --> 00:18:42.760
of practice.

00:18:42.760 --> 00:18:46.390
And I had a very profound
experience when I was there.

00:18:46.390 --> 00:18:49.330
And I think, like many
profound experiences,

00:18:49.330 --> 00:18:51.400
it doesn't sound like
much in words, perhaps.

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:54.340
But it really
changed a lot for me.

00:18:54.340 --> 00:18:58.490
And that was some sense
that prior to that moment,

00:18:58.490 --> 00:19:01.210
I had thought of
love as a commodity,

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:04.990
very much like a package
in someone else's hands.

00:19:04.990 --> 00:19:08.500
And it was in their power
to deliver it unto me

00:19:08.500 --> 00:19:10.810
or to take it away from me.

00:19:10.810 --> 00:19:15.167
And if someone took it
away from me, it was gone.

00:19:15.167 --> 00:19:17.250
Every breath, there was,
like, no love in my life.

00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:21.300
It was a little bit like the UPS
person standing on my doorstep,

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:23.930
looking at the address,
thinking, I don't think so,

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:24.930
and going the other way.

00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:33.160
Whereas if I see love as an
ability, it's within me, right?

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:34.800
It's within my power.

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:38.340
And other people or
circumstances or art--

00:19:38.340 --> 00:19:40.290
I mean, so many things
might enliven it

00:19:40.290 --> 00:19:43.030
and awaken that capacity.

00:19:43.030 --> 00:19:46.360
They might enrich it.

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:48.631
They might threaten it.

00:19:48.631 --> 00:19:50.960
They might make it
very, very difficult.

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:53.510
But it's not in their
hands, ultimately.

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:55.770
It's in mine.

00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:57.280
And that was hugely empowering.

00:19:57.280 --> 00:20:00.190
Love is not a feeling;
it's an ability.

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:06.190
And that really is the thread
that runs throughout this work.

00:20:06.190 --> 00:20:09.980
So the whole first
section of the book

00:20:09.980 --> 00:20:14.390
is about love for oneself, not
in a narcissistic, egotistical

00:20:14.390 --> 00:20:15.920
sense, of course--

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:18.560
which I think narcissism is
something very different.

00:20:18.560 --> 00:20:21.680
And it's not about
being self-preoccupied

00:20:21.680 --> 00:20:23.000
to the exclusion of others.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.840
But it's about really seeing
ourselves differently.

00:20:26.840 --> 00:20:31.200
I tell this story in there
about seeing a cartoon once

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:34.710
from the "Peanuts" comic strip.

00:20:34.710 --> 00:20:37.560
And the two characters are
Lucy and Charlie Brown.

00:20:37.560 --> 00:20:42.630
And Lucy says to Charlie Brown,
you know what your problem is?

00:20:42.630 --> 00:20:45.451
The problem with you
is that you're you.

00:20:45.451 --> 00:20:47.580
And in the second frame,
poor Charlie Brown

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:50.430
says, well, what in the
world can I do about that?

00:20:50.430 --> 00:20:51.930
Then in the third
and final frame,

00:20:51.930 --> 00:20:55.200
Lucy says, I don't pretend
to be able to give advice.

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:58.860
I merely point out the problem.

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:01.200
And somehow, whenever I
was walking by the desk

00:21:01.200 --> 00:21:04.650
that this cartoon was
on, my eye would always

00:21:04.650 --> 00:21:06.390
fall on that precise
line-- the problem

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:08.430
with you is that you're you.

00:21:08.430 --> 00:21:13.260
It's like if you really knew
who you were, big problem.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:15.810
Because that Lucy-dominant
voice had been so strong

00:21:15.810 --> 00:21:17.880
in my earlier life.

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:20.790
And I will also say that
through particularly mindfulness

00:21:20.790 --> 00:21:23.940
meditation tools,
I'd learned to have

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:28.680
a very different relationship
to Lucy, which was basically

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:32.310
seeing that voice,
hearing that message,

00:21:32.310 --> 00:21:35.810
and being able to
respond with, hi, Lucy,

00:21:35.810 --> 00:21:39.960
or chill out, Lucy, or have
a seat, have a cup of tea,

00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:41.170
just relax.

00:21:41.170 --> 00:21:43.190
Instead of like, oh my
god, Lucy's still here.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:45.540
I've been meditating all these
years and Lucy's still here.

00:21:45.540 --> 00:21:47.280
All that money in therapy,
and Lucy's still here.

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:48.196
What a terrible thing.

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:53.247
Or you're right, Lucy.

00:21:53.247 --> 00:21:54.080
You're always right.

00:21:56.690 --> 00:21:59.630
So that kind of creative
domain in between,

00:21:59.630 --> 00:22:02.360
where we can respond
very, very differently,

00:22:02.360 --> 00:22:05.960
is really-- that's the land
of mindfulness right there.

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:09.180
So how do we relate to
ourselves differently?

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:11.790
Having a sense almost of
a kind of innate dignity

00:22:11.790 --> 00:22:14.970
that exists within
us, that we can

00:22:14.970 --> 00:22:17.880
design our life
around and respond

00:22:17.880 --> 00:22:22.160
to others in the same way.

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:25.160
And the second
section of the book

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:28.950
was really about
love for an other,

00:22:28.950 --> 00:22:31.700
whether it's a
partner or a parent

00:22:31.700 --> 00:22:35.800
or a child or a friend or
a colleague or whatever.

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:44.370
And when I was first kind
of researching the book,

00:22:44.370 --> 00:22:46.740
I met with a lot of groups
and a lot of people.

00:22:46.740 --> 00:22:52.030
I was really seeking stories
and people's experiences.

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:56.490
The first time I met with a
group, this man raised his hand

00:22:56.490 --> 00:23:01.440
and he said, most people
think of a good relationship

00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:03.210
as 50-50.

00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:07.170
My dog and I were 100-100.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:08.210
And I loved that.

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:18.240
And the real part comes in in
that the sense of generosity,

00:23:18.240 --> 00:23:21.472
connection, caring is real.

00:23:21.472 --> 00:23:22.180
It's not feigned.

00:23:22.180 --> 00:23:24.510
It's not coerced.

00:23:24.510 --> 00:23:26.910
It's not forced.

00:23:26.910 --> 00:23:28.480
So here's a little section.

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:32.239
"For example, no matter
what we think we should do,

00:23:32.239 --> 00:23:33.780
I don't think you
can coerce yourself

00:23:33.780 --> 00:23:35.670
into loving your
neighbor or your boss

00:23:35.670 --> 00:23:37.940
when you can't stand them.

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:40.520
But if you try to understand
your feelings of dislike

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:43.010
with mindfulness and
compassion, being

00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:45.770
sure not to forget
self-compassion,

00:23:45.770 --> 00:23:48.920
you create the
possibility for change.

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:52.460
Your neighbor or your boss may
still do things that annoy you,

00:23:52.460 --> 00:23:54.680
but the anger and tightness
you feel in your chest

00:23:54.680 --> 00:23:59.300
whenever you see them is bound
to diminish, leaving you freer

00:23:59.300 --> 00:24:03.720
and more available for love."

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:06.720
This is basically
what we do, you know?

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:09.945
It's not to try to
pretend in any way-- well,

00:24:09.945 --> 00:24:14.310
I'm sure this man really loved
his dog more than anything.

00:24:14.310 --> 00:24:17.580
You know, it's not to enter a
state of hypocrisy or pretense,

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:20.550
or certainly not to try to
force yourself into anything,

00:24:20.550 --> 00:24:23.550
but it's awakening to
different possibilities.

00:24:23.550 --> 00:24:27.960
You know what it's like when
you're sure you know somebody,

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:29.770
and then you find out
something about them,

00:24:29.770 --> 00:24:33.350
and it's like,
that's a surprise?

00:24:33.350 --> 00:24:39.400
And the sense of almost like
awe that happens in that moment.

00:24:39.400 --> 00:24:42.650
Like whoa, who
could have guessed?

00:24:42.650 --> 00:24:45.660
I didn't know you did that,
or I didn't know whatever.

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:49.960
I also tell this story in
the book about assumptions

00:24:49.960 --> 00:24:54.460
and how a friend of mine who's
a writer gave a talk somewhere.

00:24:54.460 --> 00:25:00.860
And he, in the
context of the talk,

00:25:00.860 --> 00:25:03.470
he spoke about Proust
and reading Proust

00:25:03.470 --> 00:25:06.590
and "Remembrances
of Things Past,"

00:25:06.590 --> 00:25:10.162
which had been a very
important book for him

00:25:10.162 --> 00:25:11.120
when he was in college.

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:13.940
And afterwards he was
having dinner somewhere.

00:25:13.940 --> 00:25:19.540
And this woman came up to
him and said, I have been--

00:25:19.540 --> 00:25:20.680
I was at your talk.

00:25:20.680 --> 00:25:23.560
And his heart sank
because he immediately

00:25:23.560 --> 00:25:24.960
had a judgment about her.

00:25:24.960 --> 00:25:27.520
He thought, well, she's
probably really poorly educated

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:29.305
and she doesn't look that smart.

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:34.480
And then she said
to him, the thing

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:37.330
is, I find reading Proust
in the original French much

00:25:37.330 --> 00:25:38.790
more fulfilling.

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:44.340
And it was like, oh,
OK, there you go.

00:25:44.340 --> 00:25:46.390
You know, so it's actually
a tremendous sense

00:25:46.390 --> 00:25:51.610
of discovery and
exploration to experiment

00:25:51.610 --> 00:25:55.500
with how we pay attention
so that we can actually open

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:58.850
and we can actually listen.

00:25:58.850 --> 00:26:01.190
And then the whole third
section of the book

00:26:01.190 --> 00:26:05.510
is about love for all beings
and love for life itself.

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:10.070
And this is really interesting.

00:26:10.070 --> 00:26:12.410
In some ways it's
almost more interesting

00:26:12.410 --> 00:26:14.930
these days than it has been.

00:26:14.930 --> 00:26:19.260
It's very interesting,
and difficult, of course,

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:22.390
and demands a tremendous
amount of understanding.

00:26:22.390 --> 00:26:23.790
Like, what do we mean?

00:26:23.790 --> 00:26:26.090
Do we mean complacency?

00:26:26.090 --> 00:26:27.420
Do we mean compliance?

00:26:27.420 --> 00:26:29.390
Do we mean acquiescence?

00:26:29.390 --> 00:26:33.810
Do we mean kind of liberated
understanding that's

00:26:33.810 --> 00:26:37.350
not so afraid, that
isn't holding ourselves

00:26:37.350 --> 00:26:42.400
or others in a kind of
prison of certainty?

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:44.180
What do we mean?

00:26:44.180 --> 00:26:46.930
Because certainly, if it
means liking everybody,

00:26:46.930 --> 00:26:48.590
that makes no sense.

00:26:48.590 --> 00:26:51.000
In fact, the last
group that I did,

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:54.010
as I was trying to
collect people's stories

00:26:54.010 --> 00:27:00.710
and things like that, somebody
said to me, in my life,

00:27:00.710 --> 00:27:03.110
it was always said,
or it was just

00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:07.515
the assumption that
loving somebody was

00:27:07.515 --> 00:27:15.190
a supreme, rare, rarefied,
precious, unusual way

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:17.672
of relating, whereas
you liked everybody.

00:27:17.672 --> 00:27:18.880
I mean, you just like people.

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:19.705
It's much lower.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:24.349
And he said, you're
reversing it.

00:27:24.349 --> 00:27:25.390
You're turning it around.

00:27:25.390 --> 00:27:27.181
You're saying, yeah,
we can love everybody,

00:27:27.181 --> 00:27:30.450
but liking somebody,
that's rare, perhaps.

00:27:30.450 --> 00:27:31.330
I thought about it.

00:27:31.330 --> 00:27:34.000
And I said, you're right, I am.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:35.860
Because it's not love
in the sense of I

00:27:35.860 --> 00:27:37.640
want to spend tremendous
time with you,

00:27:37.640 --> 00:27:39.130
I want to spend
my life with you.

00:27:39.130 --> 00:27:40.060
It's not romance.

00:27:40.060 --> 00:27:46.420
It's not even saying, yeah,
let's go to the movies,

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:46.920
you know?

00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:53.270
It's that fundamental sense
of acknowledging connection

00:27:53.270 --> 00:27:54.950
and realizing we're
kind of all in this

00:27:54.950 --> 00:27:57.500
together, like we're
all the traffic.

00:27:57.500 --> 00:28:00.459
That's love as the way
I'm using the word.

00:28:00.459 --> 00:28:02.000
And you may not like
somebody at all.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:05.960
And you may decide,
you know what, it's not

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:09.691
in the sense of a balanced kind
of compassion including myself,

00:28:09.691 --> 00:28:11.690
it's not in the cards
right now that we're going

00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:12.960
to spend any time together.

00:28:12.960 --> 00:28:14.420
That's just not right.

00:28:14.420 --> 00:28:18.350
Or my best guess of the most
appropriate way, the most

00:28:18.350 --> 00:28:22.040
skillful way to relate in this
moment is strong boundaries.

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:25.880
It's kind of a fierce message.

00:28:25.880 --> 00:28:27.480
It's tough love.

00:28:27.480 --> 00:28:29.120
There's all kinds
of possibilities

00:28:29.120 --> 00:28:33.110
in terms of how we
actualize our relationship.

00:28:33.110 --> 00:28:37.820
But that inner sense
of feeling, OK, we're

00:28:37.820 --> 00:28:40.280
kind of all in this
together, what's it like?

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:42.246
What would it be like to be you?

00:28:42.246 --> 00:28:47.350
To translate some
difficult actions

00:28:47.350 --> 00:28:51.940
into actions that are produced
by pain, that cause more

00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:53.920
pain and suffering, you know?

00:28:53.920 --> 00:28:57.970
To really stretch, to examine
and be creative about the ways

00:28:57.970 --> 00:28:59.350
that we relate.

00:28:59.350 --> 00:29:05.780
Openness to the possibility
of loving everybody,

00:29:05.780 --> 00:29:07.670
even if we don't like
everyone very much.

00:29:07.670 --> 00:29:09.950
So I also tell this
story in the book

00:29:09.950 --> 00:29:16.100
about once spending time with
this man named Myles Horton who

00:29:16.100 --> 00:29:19.490
founded a school many years
ago called the Highlander Folk

00:29:19.490 --> 00:29:19.994
School--

00:29:19.994 --> 00:29:22.160
I think it still exists,
but it has a different name

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:23.360
now-- in Tennessee.

00:29:23.360 --> 00:29:25.610
But it was like a training
school for the civil rights

00:29:25.610 --> 00:29:30.365
movement in the US and the very
early environmental movement.

00:29:32.900 --> 00:29:37.340
So we ended up-- he and I end
up spending a day together.

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:41.480
And I talked to him about
loving-kindness meditation.

00:29:41.480 --> 00:29:43.670
And he sort of snorted at me.

00:29:43.670 --> 00:29:45.380
And he said, oh, Marty--

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:47.230
Martin Luther King, Jr.--

00:29:47.230 --> 00:29:48.980
Marty used to say
to me all the time,

00:29:48.980 --> 00:29:50.780
you got to love everybody.

00:29:50.780 --> 00:29:52.730
And I used to say, no, I don't.

00:29:52.730 --> 00:29:56.000
I only have to love the people
that deserve to be loved.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.150
And Marty would laugh
and say, no, you've

00:29:58.150 --> 00:30:00.860
got to love everybody.

00:30:00.860 --> 00:30:04.440
And prior to this book, I
so rarely told that story.

00:30:04.440 --> 00:30:07.950
But I remember that
every time I told

00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:11.220
the story, somebody
would come back at me

00:30:11.220 --> 00:30:13.890
and say something like, look
what happened to him, you know?

00:30:13.890 --> 00:30:15.660
He got assassinated.

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:18.840
As though it was the love
that weakened him, right?

00:30:18.840 --> 00:30:23.940
And if he'd been vicious and
angry and hostile and hateful,

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:25.950
he would have been safe.

00:30:25.950 --> 00:30:28.560
He wouldn't have been vulnerable
to anyone else's actions.

00:30:28.560 --> 00:30:34.640
And I think that projection of
causality is very interesting.

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:36.090
Look at that.

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:39.220
So the fundamental question
is, what do we think love is?

00:30:39.220 --> 00:30:41.410
And does it bring us down?

00:30:41.410 --> 00:30:42.890
Does it make us stupid?

00:30:42.890 --> 00:30:44.980
Does it make us sentimental?

00:30:44.980 --> 00:30:47.650
Or can it be this
kind of clarifying

00:30:47.650 --> 00:30:51.880
vision of, really, the
way the world actually is

00:30:51.880 --> 00:30:55.117
and how we can respond to it?

