00:44:48.780 --> 00:44:50.406
Simple, But Not Easy."

00:44:50.406 --> 00:44:52.380
Because you know, it's not easy.

00:44:55.220 --> 00:45:01.130
There's a certain-- it's like
a funny combination, I think,

00:45:01.130 --> 00:45:06.500
of loving and
letting go, which is

00:45:06.500 --> 00:45:12.590
the hallmark of a relationship
with an adult child.

00:45:12.590 --> 00:45:15.780
And it's funny, I was doing a
Skype session with a friend.

00:45:15.780 --> 00:45:18.970
I was on the east coast and
they were in California.

00:45:18.970 --> 00:45:24.020
It was a friend's yoga
teacher training group.

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:27.950
And I was talking about
within the Buddhist tradition,

00:45:27.950 --> 00:45:30.350
there's this term
called equanimity, which

00:45:30.350 --> 00:45:31.610
doesn't mean indifference.

00:45:31.610 --> 00:45:35.090
It doesn't mean
coldness or withdrawal.

00:45:35.090 --> 00:45:37.570
It means balance.

00:45:37.570 --> 00:45:39.070
And it's the balance
born of wisdom.

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:41.240
It's like perspective.

00:45:41.240 --> 00:45:45.200
In any compassionate act,
or the examples often used

00:45:45.200 --> 00:45:48.920
in that tradition of a
parent with an adult child,

00:45:48.920 --> 00:45:52.910
you know, you love them,
you care about them,

00:45:52.910 --> 00:45:55.970
you're on their side, you want
things to go well for them.

00:45:55.970 --> 00:45:59.077
And you can't make their
decisions for them.

00:45:59.077 --> 00:46:00.910
You can't say, well,
this is your livelihood

00:46:00.910 --> 00:46:01.970
and this is your partner.

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:04.160
This is, you know,
your course of life.

00:46:04.160 --> 00:46:06.110
Life is not like that.

00:46:06.110 --> 00:46:08.840
And so it's not
apathy or rejection.

00:46:08.840 --> 00:46:15.270
But it's a kind of understanding
that gives us a sense of space,

00:46:15.270 --> 00:46:17.070
like being able to breathe.

00:46:17.070 --> 00:46:19.800
So it's a combination of the
love and compassion, and also

00:46:19.800 --> 00:46:21.284
that kind of openness.

00:46:21.284 --> 00:46:22.950
So apparently there
were a lot of people

00:46:22.950 --> 00:46:27.180
in this room in that yoga
teacher training program

00:46:27.180 --> 00:46:28.900
who had young children.

00:46:28.900 --> 00:46:31.710
And they were clamoring to say,
it's like that with young kids,

00:46:31.710 --> 00:46:32.397
too.

00:46:32.397 --> 00:46:34.230
You know, it's not just
when they're adults.

00:46:34.230 --> 00:46:36.020
It's just like that.

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:38.040
You know, so it's
kind of an extension

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:40.050
of that understanding.

00:46:40.050 --> 00:46:42.427
And you know, sometimes
we're on one side,

00:46:42.427 --> 00:46:44.010
and sometimes we're
on the other side.

00:46:44.010 --> 00:46:45.870
And it's just being
aware of that.

00:46:45.870 --> 00:46:50.220
And learning how to communicate,
which is no easy feat anywhere.

00:46:50.220 --> 00:46:51.990
How do you communicate
to a colleague?

00:46:51.990 --> 00:46:55.170
How do you communicate to a
person you're supervising?

00:46:55.170 --> 00:46:59.280
Clearly, you know, there
are some tools that

00:46:59.280 --> 00:47:02.730
are kind of somewhat cliched,
maybe, your formulae,

00:47:02.730 --> 00:47:03.600
but actually work.

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:06.030
Like, you know, if you're
supervising someone,

00:47:06.030 --> 00:47:08.670
it's not that useful to
say, you're an idiot.

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:10.350
It's much more
useful to say, well,

00:47:10.350 --> 00:47:12.922
when the memo six
weeks later, whatever.

00:47:12.922 --> 00:47:14.880
Because "you're an idiot"
actually doesn't even

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:17.250
give that person the
information they need should

00:47:17.250 --> 00:47:19.320
they want to change, right?

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:22.130
So we learn how to
communicate in a way that

00:47:22.130 --> 00:47:26.370
is more expressive of, OK,
being on the same side,

00:47:26.370 --> 00:47:27.180
wanting you to--

00:47:27.180 --> 00:47:28.014
AUDIENCE: Respect.

00:47:28.014 --> 00:47:28.930
SHARON SALZBERG: Yeah.

00:47:28.930 --> 00:47:31.330
Yeah.

00:47:31.330 --> 00:47:32.577
Simple, but not easy.

00:47:32.577 --> 00:47:33.160
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:47:33.160 --> 00:47:35.470
Question over here?

00:47:35.470 --> 00:47:37.930
AUDIENCE: Do you think
love or connection

00:47:37.930 --> 00:47:39.280
can happen without empathy?

00:47:43.920 --> 00:47:46.140
SHARON SALZBERG: Can it
happen without empathy?

00:47:46.140 --> 00:47:47.890
AUDIENCE: Can you have
it without empathy?

00:47:47.890 --> 00:47:50.830
It seems like empathy is
such a key part, which

00:47:50.830 --> 00:47:52.390
is part of compassion.

00:47:52.390 --> 00:47:55.424
But I didn't really hear
you use the word empathy.

00:47:55.424 --> 00:47:57.840
SHARON SALZBERG: No, I didn't
use the word empathy at all.

00:48:00.790 --> 00:48:04.270
I think empathy is in there
somewhere along the way,

00:48:04.270 --> 00:48:05.590
for sure.

00:48:05.590 --> 00:48:09.700
We would say that empathy is
like an essential building

00:48:09.700 --> 00:48:12.790
block for, say, a
state of compassion.

00:48:12.790 --> 00:48:15.070
But it's also not
considered sufficient

00:48:15.070 --> 00:48:17.490
for a state of compassion.

00:48:17.490 --> 00:48:23.630
Because as you may have a
kind of moment of empathy

00:48:23.630 --> 00:48:25.580
towards someone's situation--

00:48:25.580 --> 00:48:28.360
let's say they're having a
hard time and you sense that,

00:48:28.360 --> 00:48:31.890
and you feel that, you
resonate with that.

00:48:31.890 --> 00:48:34.520
You might genuinely have
that moment of empathy,

00:48:34.520 --> 00:48:36.750
but then respond with fear.

00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:39.210
Or with you're just
exhausted, and you think,

00:48:39.210 --> 00:48:42.570
I'm so burnt out, I
can't possibly deal.

00:48:42.570 --> 00:48:45.210
Or you might be
blaming, you know?

00:48:45.210 --> 00:48:47.320
I gave you perfectly good
advice six months ago.

00:48:47.320 --> 00:48:49.590
If you only listened,
you'd be better off.

00:48:49.590 --> 00:48:53.580
Or in the state of
compassion, you know,

00:48:53.580 --> 00:48:57.910
it also might get blurred with
that kind of savior mentality.

00:48:57.910 --> 00:49:01.560
Like, I'm going to be the
one who's going to fix you.

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:04.524
Or we might respond with
compassion and loving-kindness.

00:49:04.524 --> 00:49:06.190
So there are a lot
of elements in there,

00:49:06.190 --> 00:49:08.430
but I think empathy
is essential.

00:49:08.430 --> 00:49:12.120
AUDIENCE: OK, it sounds like
empathy isn't as sustaining.

00:49:12.120 --> 00:49:14.190
Deeper is compassion.

00:49:14.190 --> 00:49:17.010
SHARON SALZBERG: I think
it's different, you know?

00:49:17.010 --> 00:49:19.740
So in psychological
research, they

00:49:19.740 --> 00:49:21.290
say that we might--
the way they put

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:23.040
it is we might have
this state of empathy,

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:24.840
and we need this
state of empathy.

00:49:24.840 --> 00:49:25.580
We do need it.

00:49:25.580 --> 00:49:27.090
You're right.

00:49:27.090 --> 00:49:29.500
But we might over-identify
with the other person.

00:49:29.500 --> 00:49:33.030
So it's not like we're
looking at them thinking,

00:49:33.030 --> 00:49:35.700
I can sense what it
might be like for you.

00:49:35.700 --> 00:49:37.380
It's like we're there.

00:49:37.380 --> 00:49:40.140
And then it's like we're going
down with the ship, you know?

00:49:40.140 --> 00:49:45.370
So they say that empathy leads
to empathic distress, where

00:49:45.370 --> 00:49:49.140
our own feeling of being
overwhelmed with negativity

00:49:49.140 --> 00:49:50.580
is what's taken over.

00:49:50.580 --> 00:49:51.960
So there's not
room for that kind

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:56.339
of generosity and stability
of the loving response.

00:49:56.339 --> 00:49:56.880
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:49:56.880 --> 00:49:57.838
Yeah, that makes sense.

00:49:57.838 --> 00:49:58.980
Thank you.

00:49:58.980 --> 00:49:59.940
One last question.

00:49:59.940 --> 00:50:02.344
It sounds like you've
done vipassana meditation.

00:50:02.344 --> 00:50:03.510
SHARON SALZBERG: Yeah, yeah.

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:03.850
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:04.891
And you studied in Burma.

00:50:04.891 --> 00:50:09.750
And is a lot of this book
based on the attributes

00:50:09.750 --> 00:50:11.814
and the learnings of vipassana?

00:50:11.814 --> 00:50:13.230
SHARON SALZBERG:
Well, vipassana--

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:15.135
I mean, it's kind of a
complicated question.

00:50:15.135 --> 00:50:18.131
Vipassana's a term
in Pali, the language

00:50:18.131 --> 00:50:19.380
of the original Buddhist text.

00:50:19.380 --> 00:50:20.730
It means insight medi--

00:50:20.730 --> 00:50:21.660
it means insight.

00:50:21.660 --> 00:50:24.540
So vipassana meditation
is insight meditation.

00:50:24.540 --> 00:50:27.450
And there are many, many,
many strands and techniques

00:50:27.450 --> 00:50:30.930
and traditions and
lineages within that.

00:50:30.930 --> 00:50:36.010
Goenka-- S.N. Goenka,
who was my first teacher,

00:50:36.010 --> 00:50:43.210
was kind of an early
teacher in modern time

00:50:43.210 --> 00:50:45.850
outside of Burma, which
was a very closed country.

00:50:45.850 --> 00:50:50.439
When I first went to India, you
could go to Burma for 24 hours.

00:50:50.439 --> 00:50:52.230
But he had left Burma,
and he was in India.

00:50:52.230 --> 00:50:56.620
So he called his particular
style, his particular technique

00:50:56.620 --> 00:50:57.330
vipassana.

00:50:57.330 --> 00:51:00.070
So even-- it has a
much broader meaning,

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:03.620
but most people identify it with
that one way of practice, so.

00:51:03.620 --> 00:51:06.220
And when I went to Burma, it
wasn't within his tradition.

00:51:06.220 --> 00:51:09.370
I was studying with
other people by then.

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:14.230
But he was my first teacher,
so it was a hugely important

00:51:14.230 --> 00:51:15.338
relationship.

00:51:15.338 --> 00:51:16.234
Yeah.

00:51:16.234 --> 00:51:17.130
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:18.850
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:51:18.850 --> 00:51:21.760
Well, first, my definition
of what is love,

00:51:21.760 --> 00:51:23.110
I was thinking about that.

00:51:23.110 --> 00:51:26.190
I was like, I'd say it's--

00:51:26.190 --> 00:51:29.710
so I think what I'm thinking
is just self-acceptance

00:51:29.710 --> 00:51:31.080
of all wholeness.

00:51:31.080 --> 00:51:34.780
So like my dark
sides, my light sides,

00:51:34.780 --> 00:51:38.140
everything from the past to
the present and what will be.

00:51:38.140 --> 00:51:39.790
And that's-- and it isn't easy.

00:51:39.790 --> 00:51:43.390
So that's my definition.

00:51:43.390 --> 00:51:46.040
So my question is just
around the term love.

00:51:46.040 --> 00:51:48.220
So you-- I liked what you
said about Bob Thurman.

00:51:48.220 --> 00:51:50.875
And Bob Thurman is coming here,
