00:51:50.875 --> 00:51:52.000
SHARON SALZBERG: Oh, great.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:53.420
AUDIENCE: In this room, I think.

00:51:53.420 --> 00:51:53.920
Yeah.

00:51:53.920 --> 00:51:56.660
So he's talking about his new
book called "Man of Peace,"

00:51:56.660 --> 00:51:59.090
about the Dalai Lama.

00:51:59.090 --> 00:52:03.342
So my question was
around the word,

00:52:03.342 --> 00:52:05.050
because I think there's
a lot of triggers

00:52:05.050 --> 00:52:06.589
with love and loving-kindness.

00:52:06.589 --> 00:52:08.380
I like the abbreviation
of just using love.

00:52:08.380 --> 00:52:11.229
I'm going to start
using that too.

00:52:11.229 --> 00:52:12.520
But do you think it's overused?

00:52:12.520 --> 00:52:12.855
Because--

00:52:12.855 --> 00:52:13.450
SHARON SALZBERG: Love?

00:52:13.450 --> 00:52:16.060
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the word
love, in terms of-- my thought

00:52:16.060 --> 00:52:18.987
is it loses meaning over time,
like anything if you just

00:52:18.987 --> 00:52:19.820
say it all the time.

00:52:19.820 --> 00:52:21.670
So how do you know--
like, if I love you,

00:52:21.670 --> 00:52:23.020
it's like-- is that the same?

00:52:23.020 --> 00:52:24.800
Or can you share
more about that?

00:52:24.800 --> 00:52:26.200
Because I'm always struggling--

00:52:26.200 --> 00:52:28.241
I don't want to say love
unless it's really real.

00:52:28.241 --> 00:52:31.444
But at the same time,
I want to express.

00:52:31.444 --> 00:52:32.110
So what do I do?

00:52:32.110 --> 00:52:34.115
Or what can we do?

00:52:34.115 --> 00:52:36.240
SHARON SALZBERG: We can
call it real love, I guess.

00:52:36.240 --> 00:52:38.032
AUDIENCE: I'll
just say real love.

00:52:38.032 --> 00:52:39.740
SHARON SALZBERG: No,
it's very difficult.

00:52:39.740 --> 00:52:40.739
Of course it's overused.

00:52:40.739 --> 00:52:49.200
You know, I love my
manicure, I love my lamp,

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:50.880
I love my new car, sort of.

00:52:50.880 --> 00:52:55.080
Not totally, but I
would have loved it more

00:52:55.080 --> 00:52:56.950
if it was the other
color that I asked for,

00:52:56.950 --> 00:52:59.590
but it was the second choice.

00:52:59.590 --> 00:53:00.460
But I still love it.

00:53:00.460 --> 00:53:03.930
You know, so of course we
use it in so many ways.

00:53:03.930 --> 00:53:11.740
I think that in looking back
over my work in the world and--

00:53:11.740 --> 00:53:13.150
now this is my 10th book--

00:53:13.150 --> 00:53:15.220
I realized that something
that fascinates me

00:53:15.220 --> 00:53:21.740
and that has moved me a lot has
actually been redeeming words,

00:53:21.740 --> 00:53:25.760
that so many words
get kind of denigrated

00:53:25.760 --> 00:53:31.070
or used in strange ways
or take on new meanings.

00:53:31.070 --> 00:53:33.780
And I think we lose something
when we lose the word.

00:53:33.780 --> 00:53:35.780
Like, I wrote a
book called "Faith."

00:53:35.780 --> 00:53:37.540
So that was a challenge.

00:53:37.540 --> 00:53:38.990
Even my friends were aghast.

00:53:38.990 --> 00:53:41.120
You know, like, why are
you writing a book on that?

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:42.650
Because for so
many people, faith

00:53:42.650 --> 00:53:45.350
had come to mean
being silenced and not

00:53:45.350 --> 00:53:48.400
being able to ask questions and
not having a voice of your own.

00:53:48.400 --> 00:53:50.210
And of course, it
didn't mean that to me.

00:53:50.210 --> 00:53:54.550
And so I thought, OK, if we can
take back that word, we can--

00:53:54.550 --> 00:53:58.030
perhaps if it's meaningful to
someone in a different way.

00:53:58.030 --> 00:54:01.400
So I had a feeling I might be
doing something-- trying to do

00:54:01.400 --> 00:54:04.130
something like that with love.

00:54:04.130 --> 00:54:05.840
Because if we use it
in a certain way--

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:09.140
not like I love my new
car, but not totally

00:54:09.140 --> 00:54:11.690
because it's the wrong color--

00:54:11.690 --> 00:54:16.862
then I think we recapture the
power of that in that way.

00:54:16.862 --> 00:54:18.570
AUDIENCE: When you
told the two stories--

00:54:18.570 --> 00:54:23.010
one about traffic and the other
about being on the airplane--

00:54:23.010 --> 00:54:24.330
what do you think--

00:54:24.330 --> 00:54:25.830
what do you think
it takes to get

00:54:25.830 --> 00:54:27.990
to where you have
those realizations

00:54:27.990 --> 00:54:30.489
on throughout the day, right?

00:54:30.489 --> 00:54:32.280
I know people use the
word triggered, which

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:34.450
I'm starting to find overused.

00:54:34.450 --> 00:54:36.000
But you know, for you, or even--

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.580
for you, I'm curious, and then
also advice for other people,

00:54:38.580 --> 00:54:39.080
right?

00:54:39.080 --> 00:54:42.360
How do you remember everybody
else exists and the other is

00:54:42.360 --> 00:54:45.074
not the other, and you know,
the situation is what it is.

00:54:45.074 --> 00:54:46.740
I mean, what does
that-- how does that--

00:54:46.740 --> 00:54:47.970
what do you think on that?

00:54:47.970 --> 00:54:50.390
SHARON SALZBERG: I think
the meditation exercise

00:54:50.390 --> 00:54:54.480
we did is like a fractal of the
whole path in that you won't

00:54:54.480 --> 00:54:57.730
remember throughout the day,
but you can begin again.

00:54:57.730 --> 00:54:58.490
Right?

00:54:58.490 --> 00:54:59.880
And I was talking about words.

00:54:59.880 --> 00:55:03.570
You know, like at the end of a
workshop, the end of a retreat,

00:55:03.570 --> 00:55:06.540
the end of a program,
people often say, well,

00:55:06.540 --> 00:55:09.640
how can I keep the level of
concentration I got here?

00:55:09.640 --> 00:55:12.600
How can I maintain the level
of mindfulness I got here?

00:55:12.600 --> 00:55:15.790
And my usual response is, you
won't, but you can start again,

00:55:15.790 --> 00:55:17.400
you can start again
more gracefully,

00:55:17.400 --> 00:55:21.495
you can start again with
less glue, you know?

00:55:21.495 --> 00:55:24.120
With better humor, with more
kindness towards yourself.

00:55:24.120 --> 00:55:25.900
You can start again sooner.

00:55:25.900 --> 00:55:27.480
And that's what happens.

00:55:27.480 --> 00:55:28.740
You know, of course we forget.

00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:29.970
I mean, we're just human beings.

00:55:29.970 --> 00:55:31.050
AUDIENCE: After
everything you've done

00:55:31.050 --> 00:55:32.730
and as long as you've
done this, do you

00:55:32.730 --> 00:55:34.439
feel some of that
comes naturally to you?

00:55:34.439 --> 00:55:35.521
SHARON SALZBERG: Oh, yeah.

00:55:35.521 --> 00:55:36.030
Yeah.

00:55:36.030 --> 00:55:41.630
But that doesn't mean every
moment of the day, you know?

00:55:41.630 --> 00:55:43.940
AUDIENCE: So assure us that
you have some bad moments.

00:55:43.940 --> 00:55:46.106
SHARON SALZBERG: I have
some bad moments, thank you.

